====== `meow init` — Project Initialization ======

This page explains how `meow init` scaffolds new projects and the meaning of its arguments.

===== Basic usage =====
  `meow init [name] [compiler]`

  * If `name` is omitted Meow uses the current directory name and creates files in-place.
  * If `compiler` is omitted the default is `masm`.

===== What is created =====
  * `meow.yaml` — project configuration.
  * `src/` — source directory. A main file is created (language-specific if supported).
  * `tests/` — test directory.
  * `build/` — output folder.
  * `README.md`, `.gitignore`.

===== Language templates =====
After scaffolding `meow init` will attempt to generate a proper language-specific main file by invoking the project's template provider via `BuildService.CreateMainTemplateAsync`. This yields nicer, idiomatic starter files (e.g., `src/main.py`, `src/Main.java`) when compilers/runners implement `ITemplateProvider`.

If a compiler/runner does not implement `ITemplateProvider`, Meow also looks for static starter methods annotated with `StarterTemplate` on the compiler type (see `docs/templates.dokuwiki`). These annotated starters allow providing templates without creating an instance of the compiler type.

===== Overwrite behavior =====
  * Current behavior: the default `ProjectService` writes a basic main file; the `BuildService` template provider is called afterwards and will write a nicer main file if available. Existing files are not overwritten silently.
  * Future: a `--force` argument may be added to overwrite existing main files.

===== Examples =====
  * `meow init my-project go` — creates a Go project and generates `src/main.go`.
  * `meow init` — initialize in current directory (defaults to `masm`).

